idCitation.resTitle: Sublette Mule Deer Herd Migration Corridor in the Upper Green River Basin of Wyoming, 1:24,000

dataExt.exDesc: The data were first collected in 2003. Field data included in this analysis continued through 2015.

dataIdInfo.idPurp: These data identify the official migration corridor for the Sublette mule deer herd as designated by the Wyoming Game and Fish Department (WGFD).
dataIdInfo.idAbs: These data represent the WGFD edited version of statistically based polygons derived from GPS collar data on mule deer migrating in the Upper Green River Basin. The animals collared are from the Mesa, Ryegrass, and Superior winter ranges from 2003 through 2015. The GPS data were analyzed using the Brownian Bridge Movement Model (BBMM),which produced polygons based on where animals traversed from winter range to summer range (and back) and how much time they spent along the way. The original data were edited to be more manageable on the ground as the WGFD works with land management agencies during land use planning.

dataLineage.statement:
Statistically produced corridor data were received by the WGFD in 2016 based on a sample size of 143 deer and 427 migration sequences. The data required some clean up to become more logically usable on the ground. The original data were separated by winter range complex, and each had use categories defined by the number of animals using the same space. There were single animal polygons, then low, moderate, and high use polygons. Low use represented less than 9% of the herd population, moderate represented between 10-20%, while high use represented more than 20% of the overall population. The Wyoming Game and Fish Commission considers a big game corridor as being defined by the use of an area by more than one animal. Where the single animal use of the separate winter range complexes crossed with other animals, the polygons were incorporated into the main corridor as they represent more than one animal.
A few rules were agreed upon by the Wildlife Division and Habitat Protection Program staff at the WGFD to follow for data editing. Those included any islands within the corridor polygon that were under 20 acres were deleted (i.e.absorbed and became part of the corridor), and such islands outside the corridor under 20 acres were deleted. If polygons greater than 20 acres were closer than 0.5 mi, then professional judgment was used in the effort to connect the polygons. Regional biologists reviewed the data and provided their feedback for minor discretionary edits.

dataSource.srcDesc: The source data were BBMM statistical data based on GPS collar information.

prcStep.stepDesc: After the data were approved by herd segment or winter range complex, the data were merged and dissolved to produce one homogenous corridor polygon.
